gmd:abstract.gco:CharacterString: This dataset shows the natural regions and their subsections in Indiana.

gmd:purpose.gco:CharacterString: This dataset was compiled to provide boundaries for the natural regions in Indiana. It is intended for a variety of uses by the public recognizing that the horizontal accuracy does not support high precision applications.

gmd:supplementalInformation.gco:CharacterString: This dataset, as well as many others, was compiled for mapping and download as part of the Web site titled "A GIS Atlas for Indiana," funded by the Indiana Department of Transportation. Many publicly available datasets were created, edited, and compiled inclusion on the Web site where users can download data or map online using ESRI ArcIMS. Many public data sources, not created in conjunction with the statewide project, were obtained by Web site download, contacting originators, and creating spatial files from tabular data. A range of layer editing was used, specific to each layer, from full creation, to data cleaning, to only reformatting metadata. The level of editing done by BLA or the Indiana Geological Survey (IGS) is fully disclosed in the process steps of this metadata; credit for the information is retained by the originator.

gmd:description.gco:CharacterString: The printed map published in the paper by Michael Homoya was digitized at a scale of 1:800,000 by the Indiana Natural Heritage Data Center.

Bernardin-Lochmueller and Associates obtained the shapefile named "NATREG83.SHP"from the Indiana Natural Heritage Data Center. Software-generated fields which were deemed unnecessary to the dataset were deleted. These fields that were deleted are: "area," "perimeter," "natreg," and "natreg_id." This metadata was written using information obtained by discussion. The file was obtained in UTM Zone 16 and all produced products were kept in this projection.

This metadata was pre-parsed and parsed using CNS (Chew and Spit, v 2.6.1) and MP (Metadata Parser, v 2.7.1) software written by Peter N. Schweitzer (United States Geological Survey). The errors generated by MP were all addressed and corrected, except that no values were assigned to "Abscissa_Resolution" and "Ordinate_Resolution."
